2026-02-16 11:13:19 [DEBUG] openai._base_client:485 - Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'headers': {'X-Stainless-Raw-Response': 'true'}, 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-6d87baef-1234-41b2-bd9e-12bd01ded7ba', 'content': None, 'json_data': {'messages': [{'content': '\nYou are an early-warning disaster & event monitor.\n\nRead the following news/social/web items from Nigeria\nin period February 14, 2026.\n\nReturn ONLY events that are:\n- natural disasters (flood, storm, earthquake, wildfire, etc.)\n- major transport disruptions (port closure, strike, border issue, etc.)\n- other high-impact events (protests, accidents, supply chain crisis)\n\nFormat each as :\nEVENT_TYPE | short description | current impact level (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW) | source snippet\n\nIf no relevant events → return exactly:\nNO_DISASTER_OR_MAJOR_EVENTS\n\nItems:\nSince taking up the concession in the late 1990s, Cornelder has overseen significant investment in port infrastructure and equipment, positioning Beira as a competitive regional alternative to larger southern African ports.\n\nOperationally, there has been no indication of disruption at the port. Terminal activities continue as normal, and there has been no announcement from Mozambican authorities suggesting a review, suspension or alteration of the concession arrangements.\n\n## Expansion plans under a new spotlight [...] The two carriers said the move would be limited in scope and carefully managed. Additional Gemini services — specifically the AE12 and AE15 — may also be routed through the Red Sea and Suez Canal at a later stage, subject to security conditions.\n\nFurther guidance to customers and stakeholders will be issued if and when those changes are implemented. No wider adjustments to the Gemini network are planned at this stage.\n\nMaersk and Hapag-Lloyd stressed that the rerouting has been designed to minimise disruption to customers while maintaining the schedule reliability that underpins the Gemini Cooperation. [...] First, recent background reports point to major challenges facing the development of the soft infrastructure of customs and regulations. Others have pointed to the corridor’s unclear commercial viability. Ships having to call at the secondary port of Lobito will incur higher costs. There’s also competition from other routes – mostly, the Chinese-built Tazara railway, connecting Zambia to Dar-es-Salaam.\n\nSecond, the economic model at the heart of the Lobito corridor is anything but a break with exploitative extractivism. Throughout Angolan history, primary commodities have left the country, while hopes for broad-based growth have repeatedly been frustrated.\n\nBeat Simon, Chief Operating Officer – Logistics at DP World, said the data confirms that disruption is no longer a short-term phenomenon.\n\n“Supply-chain disruption is no longer a temporary shock; it is a recurring drain on growth, profitability and customer trust,” Simon said. “In some regions, businesses are effectively planning around the loss of weeks or months of productive time each year.”\n\nHowever, the report notes that the regions under the greatest pressure are also responding with urgency. More than 90% of businesses in Sub-Saharan Africa and the GCC expect to increase investment in logistics over the next year, while 86% of companies in MENA plan to do the same. [...] Companies strengthening multiple logistics capabilities — from factory logistics and inbound flows to warehousing and digital coordination — report significantly lower disruption costs. In consumer goods, firms investing in four or more logistics areas recorded disruption costs around 76% lower than low-investment peers.\n\nCustomer impact is now close to universal, with between 80% and 95% of respondents reporting increased complaints linked to logistics failures.\n\nLasting reputational damage, however, is concentrated in specific markets, notably Sub-Saharan Africa and France, while firms in North America and the UK report higher complaint volumes but more resilient brand perceptions. [...] Africa Ports & Ships\n\nGlobal trade is no longer recovering from isolated shocks but operating under sustained strain, with companies across parts of the Global South losing months of productivity, millions of dollars and long-term customer trust as supply-chain disruption becomes a defining feature of the operating environment.\n\nThese are among the conclusions of DP World’s Without Logistics report, based on a global survey of 680 senior logistics and supply-chain decision-makers across eight industries and nine regions.\n\nThe study finds that while disruption is now commonplace worldwide, its impact is most severe and persistent in Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA), the Middle East and North Africa (MENA), and the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states.\n\n#### What you should know\n\nThe Lagos State Government routinely cordons off roadways, partially or fully, for events like marathons, road rehabilitation, and repairs. Traffic advisories help residents plan their journeys to avoid delays.\n\nCommuters in Victoria Island, Lekki, and surrounding areas should expect intermittent road closures throughout February 14 and follow official advisories for guidance.\n\nCaleb Obiowo\n\n### Caleb Obiowo\n\nCaleb Obiowo is a graduate of Urban and Regional Planning from the University of Uyo. At Nairametrics, he covers transport and logistics in Nigeria, along with real estate, construction, and aviation. He focuses on delivering clear, easy-to-understand stories and often digs deeper into industry issues through conversations with key players. [...] Nairametrics\nNairametrics\n\n# Lagos announces VI, Lekki traffic diversions for Feb. 14 marathon\n\nCaleb Obiowo by Caleb Obiowo\nTraffic diversion,\n\nThe Lagos State Government has announced major traffic diversions and partial road closures across Victoria Island and Lekki ahead of the February 14, 2026, Access Bank Lagos City Marathon.\n\nThe disclosure was made in a statement signed by the Lagos State Commissioner for Transportation, Oluwaseun Osiyemi.\n\nMotorists have been urged to plan ahead and use alternative routes, as multiple roads along the 42km and 10km race routes will be blocked from midnight and reopened intermittently as runners progress.\n\n### MoreStories\n\nProf. Joash Amupitan confirmed by Senate as new INEC Chairman [...] ### INEC to expand technology deployment for 2027 elections – Amupitan\n\ntinted glass permits\n\n### FG redeploys police from VIP escorts after Kwara attack\n\n#### What they are saying\n\nThe government said the 2026 marathon would feature two simultaneous races across major parts of Victoria Island and Lekki.\n\nMotorists are advised to plan trips early, use alternative transport options, and be patient. The temporary closures are part of safety and logistics arrangements for the 11th edition of the marathon.\n\n#### Race routes and road management plan\n\nThe 42km race will start at Ahmadu Bello Way near MRS Gas Station and proceed along the entire Coastal Road to the finish.\n\nOfficials will prevent unauthorized access to race corridors and guide motorists through alternative routes.\n\nAfter weeks of tension and protests that disrupted operations at the Murtala Muhammed International Airport (MMIA), the Federal Airports Authority of Nigeria (FAAN) and Customs Licensed Cargo Agents have officially reached a compromise on new cargo port charges. The agreement was achieved at a stakeholders’ meeting held on Monday, February 2026, at the MMIA Terminal 2 Conference Room, chaired by the Director of Cargo Development and...\n\n### Qatar redefining pet travel, 54.3 million travellers passed through Doha in 2025\n\nIn 2025, 54.3 million travellers from around the world passed through\n\n### FAAN achieves milestone with elite dual ISO certifications\n\nThis is a significant milestone for the Nigerian aviation sector as [...] FAAN, Customs cargo agent reach deal on port charge tariffs at MMIA\n\n  After weeks of tension and protests that disrupted operations at the Murtala Muhammed\n February 08, 2026\n\n  African airlines’ traffic rose 10.3% in 2025, scrambled to accommodate demand\n\n  The International Air Transport Association (IATA) has said that December 2025 traffic for\n February 04, 2026\n\n  Green Africa in rebuilding phase, acquires second ATR72-600 airplane, partners Access Bank\n\n  In a significant move for Nigeria’s aviation landscape, Green Africa has followed up on its\n\n### Overland Airways Expands Network with New Flight to Freetown\n\nDecember 15, 2024\n\n### Arik Air reconnects Asaba October 17\n\nOctober 12, 2024\n\n### TAAG Angola Airlines incorporates first A220-300 into fleet\n\nOctober 03, 2024 [...] January 24, 2026\n\n### United earned $59.1 billion operating revenue, highest in airline’s history\n\nJanuary 21, 2026\n\n## Views\n\n### Safety compliance, regulation in Nigerian aviation: Beyond safety culture rules\n\n### Opinion: Nigeria’s Aviation Sector Soars: Modernisation, Strategic Partnerships Drive New Era of Growth\n\n### OPINION: It’s turbulent but not dangerous\n\n### Why CORSIA Matters, By Thompsen, IATA Senior Vice-President, Economist\n\n### MMA2: PPP model still holds the ace\n\n## News\n\n### FAAN, Customs cargo agent reach deal on port charge tariffs at MMIA\n\nStakeholders Make Demands At Northeast Regional Hearing For Constitution Review\n\n  Updated : 10th February 2026 04:12 PM\n Crowds Pay Respect To Late Jota & Brother\n\n  Dignitaries, Fans Mourn Jota and Brother, Andre\n\n  Updated : 10th February 2026 08:48 AM\n Group Tells Tinubu To Extend Customs CG\'s Tenure\n\n  CECOE Calls on Presidency To Retain CG Adeniyi For Sustained Customs Reforms\n\n  Updated : 9th February 2026 05:09 PM\n Wike Defends Money Spent On BTICC\n\n  Minister Reveals Investment On Conference Paying Off\n\n  Updated : 9th February 2026 05:09 PM\n IGP says Rise of "One Chance" Robbers, A G